Predicting Loans for Universal Bank¶

Remember: You were recently hired as a data scientist by Universal Bank. You now have a new tool to use to help the VP predict who might take out a personal loan. Use the data from previous weeks for this assignment.

You are going to investigate using decision trees to help predict personal loans. You know not to use zip codes as an explanatory variable but you can use all the other data available.

1. Do you need to make any changes to the data to run a decision tree classifier? If so, what do you change and why? If not, why not? (2 points)¶

In [1]:
# code or markdown here

In assignment 2, it is discussed that zip code can be misused,
so I keep all variables in the dataset except Zip Code.

52 data have a negative value of number of years of professional work experience, which does not make sense in real life,
so I delete those data.

For a decision tree classifier, it requires that all of the attributes are categorical,
so I classify 'Education' according to text description and classify continuous attributes according to their mean,
then convert all attributes to dummy variables.

Also, I exclude 'Securities Account','CD Account','Online',and 'CreditCard'
since they will make the decision tree much more complicated but their effects are negligible.

newdf=df.copy()

#age
condition_age = [(newdf['Age']<40),
                 (newdf['Age']>=40)&(newdf['Age']<50),
                 (newdf['Age']>=50)]
values_age = ['under40','40to50','over50']
newdf['Age new'] = np.select(condition_age,values_age)

#experience
condition_experience = [(newdf['Experience']<=20),
                        (newdf['Experience']>20)]
values_experience = ['<=20','>20']
newdf['Experience new'] = np.select(condition_experience,values_experience)

#income
condition_Income = [(newdf['Income']<70),
                    (newdf['Income']>=70)]
values_Income = ['<=70','>70']
newdf['Income new'] = np.select(condition_Income,values_Income)

#family
condition_Family = [(newdf['Family']==1),
                    (newdf['Family']>1)]
values_Family = ['Single','Not Single']
newdf['Family new'] = np.select(condition_Family,values_Family)

#CCAvg
condition_CCAvg = [(newdf['CCAvg']<=2), 
                   (newdf['CCAvg']>2)]
values_CCAvg = ['<=2','>2']
newdf['CCAvg new'] = np.select(condition_CCAvg,values_CCAvg)

#education
condition_Education = [(newdf['Education']==1),
                       (newdf['Education']==2),
                       (newdf['Education']==3)]
values_Education = ['Undergraduate','Graduate','Advanced']
newdf['Education new'] = np.select(condition_Education,values_Education)

#Mortgage
condition_Mortgage = [(newdf['Mortgage']==0),
                      (newdf['Mortgage']>0)]
values_Mortgage = ['no','yes']
newdf['Mortgage new'] = np.select(condition_Mortgage,values_Mortgage)

#Personal Loan
condition_PersonalLoan = [(newdf['Personal Loan']==0),
                          (newdf['Personal Loan']==1)]
values_PersonalLoan = ['no','yes']
newdf['Personal Loan new'] = np.select(condition_PersonalLoan,values_PersonalLoan)

newdf = newdf.drop(columns=['Age','Experience','Income','Family','CCAvg','Education','Mortgage','Personal Loan'])

2. Train at least two different versions of a decision tree using both entropy and gini measures. What differences do you get in the shape of the trees? Why do you think that is? (3 points)¶

In [3]:
# code or markdown here

Though the two plots have the same size,
their shape has slight differences in branches.

The reason we get different decision tree shapes is that
the tree is constructed within different criterion parameters,
deciding where the splits happened and which split happens first.
What contributes most to the reduction in uncertainty (entropy)
can be different from what contributes most to the increase in purity (gini).
In [6]:
X = dummy.iloc[:,:-2]
y = dummy.iloc[:,-1:]

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn import tree
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion = "entropy", random_state = 12345)
dt.fit(X, y)
print(dt.tree_.max_depth) #number of split levels
print(dt.tree_.n_leaves) #total number of leaves

plt.figure(figsize=(100,20))
tree.plot_tree(dt, feature_names = X.columns,  filled=True)
plt.show()

In [4]:
# code or markdown here

Income, education, and CCAvg seem to contribute most to the reduction in uncertainty/increase in purity.
They are the first three splits according to the text representation of the tree.

This result doesn't surprise me.
These three variables are all transformed from continuous attributes,
which include a wider range of values in each class,
and thus will cause greater effects to the target variable.

5. Try pruning the tree using min_samples_split and/or min_impurity_decrease. Try at least two combinations. How does the shape change? Top predictor variables? Predictive accuracy? (3 points)¶

In [ ]:
# code or markdown here

I try four models, using two different min_samples_split parameters and two different min_impurity_decrease parameters.
They have completely different shapes.
They have the same top predictor variable, which is income,
but they have different second and following top predictor variables,
and thus have different branches in shape.

When the min_impurity_decrease parameter is 0.001, the predictive accuracy increases from 0.9192 to 0.9202.
When the min_impurity_decrease parameter is 0.01,   the predictive accuracy decrease from 0.9192 to 0.9101.
When the min_samples_splits parameter is 1% of the data size, the accuracy increases from 0.9192 to 0.9202.
When the min_samples_splits parameter is 5% of the data size,  the accuracy decrease from 0.9192 to 0.9030.
